VALUES (404, 'Landmine Reverse Lunge Video Exercise Guide', 'Quads', 'Strength', 'Landmine', 'Compound',
        'Push (Unilateral)', 'Intermediate', 'Abs, Adductors, Calves, Glutes, Hamstrings, Shoulders, Traps, Upper Back', 'The landmine reverse lunge is a reverse lunge variation and an exercise used to target the muscles of the legs. Specifically, the landmine reverse lunge is used to build your quadriceps, will also hit your hamstrings, glutes, calves, and core.
The landmine reverse lunge takes advantage of the landmine implement to provide a fixed plane of motion while also anteriorly loading the movement pattern. This allows one to better remain upright during the exercise while also providing slightly more stability than other variations.', 'Set up with your feet shoulder width apart while holding the end of a barbell in a landmine attachment at chest height.
Step back with one leg and allow both knees to bend simultaneously.
Descend until the back knee touches the floor.
Drive through the front foot and extend the knee as you stand up fully and return to the starting position.
Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.', 'Reverse lunges are a more advanced progression and should only be utilized once one has the requisite hip and core stability. In general, a proper single leg progression scheme might look like this:
Step Up
Split Squat > Front foot elevated
Reverse Lunge > Front foot elevated
Single Leg Squat to Bench
Lateral Lunge
